			<tr>
				<td colspan="2">
					
					


<font face="verdana" size="2"><p><b>Compatible races:</b></font><br>


<font face="verdana" size="1">
<a href='classes.asp?CID=31&mode=details&type=classes'>Human</a>, <a href='classes.asp?CID=97990&mode=details&type=classes'>Iksar</a>
<font face="verdana" size="3"><p><b>Guide:</b></font><br><br>
<font face="verdana" size="2">
<p><em><strong><small><font face="Verdana">Introduction</font></small></strong></em></p>

<p><a href="http://www.everlore.com/skills/default.asp?mode=1&id=11"><small><font
face="Verdana">Jump to the skills that apply to a monk</font></small></a></p>

<p><small><font face="Verdana">So you want to play a monk.  Monks can only be <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/races_classes/classes.asp?CID=31&mode=details&type=classes">human</a>.
  They are very similar to a <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/races_classes/classes.asp?CID=18&mode=details&type=races">Warrior</a>
except they really don't use weapons and definitely don't use armor, except leather.
  There weapons are there hands and feet.  You immediately get <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/skills/default.asp?mode=5&id=563">Dual Wield</a> that
allows you to use both hands for fighting.  You are in Quenos, unless you picked
Freeport as your starting point, and start out by hunting for your guild.  Its easy
to find by looking at your map in the EverQuest box.  I'll update the specifics later
this week.</font></small></p>

<p><em><strong><small><font face="Verdana">What skills you should practice.</font></small></strong></em></p>

<p><small><font face="Verdana">Three trains of thought here.  </font></small>

<ul>
  <li><small><font face="Verdana">I have heard people say you should spend all your skill
    points on <a href="http://www.everlore.com/skills/default.asp?mode=5&id=579">Mend
    Wounds</a>.  Valid point mend wounds is crucial to your survival,  but some
    think you can learn this skill by doing it constantly and raising it by hand so to speak.
      Problem is it still takes a very long time.  This is the option I chose, I
    spent almost all of my practice points here.  You could follow the next options which
    are also very valid.</font></small></li>
  <li><small><font face="Verdana">You could decide to wait and save all of your skill practice
    points for <a href="http://www.everlore.com/skills/default.asp?mode=5&id=567">Feign
    Death</a>.  Which would allow you to act as though you were dead.  This is great
    if you have mad it that far without pulling your hair out.  Still you can practice
    that skill when you get there.  I would save some for this skill, just not all.</font></small></li>
  <li><small><font face="Verdana">Last option which goes for just about any class race
    combination is spend all you practice points on <a
    href="http://www.everlore.com/skills/default.asp?mode=5&id=602">tailoring</a>,  <a
    href="http://www.everlore.com/skills/default.asp?mode=5&id=548">blacksmithing</a> or
    some other skill that suites your fancy.  The only caveat I have is, just pick one
    for a while and test it out.  Don't spread them out.  Get good at one skill and
    use it to your advantage.</font></small></li>
</ul>

<p><em><strong><small><font face="Verdana">Levels 1-3</font></small></strong></em></p>

<p><small><font face="Verdana">Before you start out make sure you have placed your combat <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/skills/default.asp?mode=5&id=576">kick ability</a> on
your shortcut bar.  There are instruction in you EverQuest Manual on how to do this.
  </font></small></p>

<p><small><font face="Verdana">You start out by going out side the Quenos gates.
  There you should be able to get yourself to level 3 in no time.  At first kill
snakes, decaying skeletons, gnoll pups, and rats.  These should be low level
creatures in great abundance, that when you right click on them, they should be equal to
you skill level.  Remember to always hit the Kick button when fighting these
creatures.  As you are pummeling them with your hands you can always quicken there
death with a few kicks.</font></small></p>

<p><small><font face="Verdana">Once you hit level 2-3 you should start to kill fire beetle
and klink warriors,  they look the same, like big spiders.  Don't forget to kill
everything else,  it pays to be thorough. </font></small></p>

<p><em><strong><small><font face="Verdana">Levels 4+</font></small></strong></em></p>

<p><small><font face="Verdana">Once you hit level 4 its time to move past the first zone
into the Quenos Hills.  There you will find larger rats and tougher Giant Bats and
gray wolves.  Stay away from rabid animals,  rabid animals, like rabid bears
wolves and the like have a disease spell that stays with you for a long time and decrease
your ability to heal and fight.  You don't want that on your for these levels.
  There are plenty of other creatures that are your same level to fight without this
little disease spell. </font></small></p>

<p><small><font face="Verdana">Once you hit level 5 go immediately to your guild in Quenos
and practice <a href="http://www.everlore.com/skills/default.asp?mode=5&id=592">Round
Kick</a>.  Round Kick is the kick upgrade, takes longer to perform, but packs more of
a punch.  You are a monk,  this is your special abilities, use them!</font></small></p>

<p><small><font face="Verdana">More to come later!</font></small></p>

<p><small><font face="Verdana">Please if you have more to add, submit new information
above.  It won't display immediately because we have to verify the content first.
  </font></small></p>

					
					</p></font>
				</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
